# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: dodge-magnum
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:dodge-magnum/1955-dodge] The **1955 Dodge** car lineup, consisting of the entry-level Coronet, Royal, and ornate Custom Royal, was a major departure for the company.
[src:dodge-magnum/1955-dodge] Driven almost out of business in 1953 and 1954, the Chrysler Corporation was revived with a $250 million loan from Prudential and new models designed by Virgil Exner.
[src:dodge-magnum/1955-dodge] The Dodge lineup was positioned as the mainstream line in Chrysler's hierarchy, between DeSoto and Plymouth.
[src:dodge-magnum/1955-dodge] The 1955 Dodge was all-new with a 120 in (3048 mm) wheelbase and 212.1 in (5387 mm) overall length, longer than the 1954 cars.
[src:dodge-magnum/1955-dodge] They shared their basic mechanicals with the DeSoto Custom, but had distinct styling.
[src:dodge-magnum/1955-dodge] These cars lasted through the 1956 model year before being replaced by an all-new 1957.
[src:dodge-magnum/1955-dodge] The **Coronet** (and **Suburban** station wagon) was the base model.
[src:dodge-magnum/1955-dodge] This was the only line to feature the 230 in3 (3.8 L) *Getaway* I6 as well as the 270 in3 (4.4 L) *Red Ram* V8.
[src:dodge-magnum/1955-dodge] Coronets were available in all body styles except the convertible.
[src:dodge-magnum/1955-dodge] Sedans feature "Coronet" badges on the fenders, while the station wagons are called "Suburban".
[src:dodge-magnum/1955-dodge] Although the hardtop coupe was officially named "Lancer", it wore only "Coronet" badges.
[src:dodge-magnum/1955-dodge] Turn signals were standard on the Royal and Custom Royal models but optional on the base Coronet.
[src:dodge-magnum/1955-dodge] The **Royal** (and **Sierra** wagon) were the next step up.
[src:dodge-magnum/1955-dodge] Featuring only the V8 engine, the Royal also lacked the 2-door sedan and wagon models available in the Coronet line.
[src:dodge-magnum/1955-dodge] Early hardtop coupes lack the "Lancer" script, although they were officially Lancers, but later models wore "Royal Lancer" badges.
[src:dodge-magnum/1955-dodge] The flagship model was the **Custom Royal**.
[src:dodge-magnum/1955-dodge] All hardtop coupe and Custom Royal-only convertible models were called "Custom Royal Lancer".
[src:dodge-magnum/1955-dodge] The Custom line featured unique chrome tailfins (although early model year cars went without this trim), special tail light surrounds, and an upscale interior.
[src:dodge-magnum/1955-dodge] Backup lights were standard on the Custom line but optional on all others.
[src:dodge-magnum/1955-dodge] The Custom Royal also featured the hemi 270 CID Super Red Ram engine.
[src:dodge-magnum/1955-dodge] The **La Femme** was a special package oriented towards women, who made up an increasing share of Dodge buyers.
[src:dodge-magnum/1955-dodge] It came in Heather Rose and Sapphire White colors and included a cape, boots, umbrella, and shoulder bag that matched the floral tapestry-like fabrics.
[src:dodge-magnum/1955-dodge] Changes to the car include built-in compartments in the seatbacks to hold these accessories.
[src:dodge-magnum/1955-dodge] The 1956 **D-500** was a high-performance model derived from the standard 1956 Dodge but differing in many ways.
[src:dodge-magnum/1955-dodge] It included a heavy duty suspension and other chassis upgrades from the New Yorker and Imperial lines, upgraded brakes, and a high-performance 315 in3 (5.2 L) Hemi-head V8.
[src:dodge-magnum/1955-dodge] A four-barrel Carter carburetor pushed output to 260 hp (194 kW) and 330 lb·ft (447 N·m).
[src:dodge-magnum/1955-dodge] The 3-speed manual transmission was standard, with the PowerFlite 2-speed automatic as an option.
[src:dodge-magnum/1955-dodge] A rare NASCAR-specific option was the D-500-1(Dash-1), which upped power to 285 hp (213 kW).
[src:dodge-magnum/1955-dodge] The D-500 originally used only the Coronet 2-door sedan and Royal Lancer hardtop and convertible bodies.
[src:dodge-magnum/1955-dodge] For the 1957 model year, Chrysler embarked on a second total linewide redesign.
[src:dodge-magnum/1955-dodge] Virgil Exner's "Forward Design" brought about cars that were bigger and more sleek than anything before, and instantly put a company that had traditionally regarded styling as unimportant on the forefront of automotive design.
[src:dodge-magnum/1955-dodge] Unfortunately, two total redesigns in as many years resulted in severe build quality and rust problems, so that many 1957 Chryslers, Dodges, and Plymouths were off the road within three years of their purchase.
[src:dodge-magnum/1955-dodge] While many of the quality issues were resolved for the 1958 model year, which brought about some minor styling tweaks, a recession struck that was particularly damaging to sales of mid-range cars.
[src:dodge-magnum/1955-dodge] Dodge production had exceeded 337,000 cars for 1957 but the 1958 total fell by over half to less than 140,000, although some of this loss was due to negative publicity from the cars' poor quality control.
[src:dodge-magnum/1955-dodge] 1959 Dodges were facelifted to gain a heavy, drooping look with hooded headlamps.
[src:dodge-magnum/1955-dodge] Production for the model year totaled 156,395 cars, a modest increase over 1958.
[src:dodge-magnum/1955-dodge] The highlight of the lineup was the performance-oriented D-500 package.
[src:dodge-magnum/1955-dodge] Power came from either a 230 cu in (4 L) flathead straight six or one of two 270 cu in (4 L) V8s.
[src:dodge-magnum/1955-dodge] The regular Red Ram V8 was standard on the Royal and optional on the Coronet.
[src:dodge-magnum/1955-dodge] A hemi V8 (the Super Red Ram) was standard on the Custom Royal.
[src:dodge-magnum/1955-dodge] A rare Power Pack was optional, consisting of a four-barrel Carter carburetor and dual exhausts good for 193 hp (144 kW; 196 PS) with the Hemi engine.
[src:dodge-magnum/1955-dodge] Two transmissions were offered: a three-speed manual with optional overdrive and Chrysler's two-speed PowerFlite automatic.
[src:dodge-magnum/1955-dodge] The PowerFlite was controlled by a dash-mounted lever, though this was changed to a push-button setup for 1956.
[src:dodge-magnum/1955-dodge] The cars used a special coil spring/kingpin suspension in front and regular leaf springs and a live axle at the rear.
[src:dodge-magnum/1955-dodge] A six-volt electrical system was updated to 12 volts in 1956.
[src:dodge-magnum/1958-dodge] The Dodge lineup was refreshed for the 1958 model year, continuing the three-line scheme of the 1955 Dodges with the entry-level Coronet, Royal, and ornate Custom Royal.
[src:dodge-magnum/1958-dodge] The Regal Lancer was added as a new top-of-the-line model in spring.
[src:dodge-magnum/1958-dodge] The 1958 Dodges shared their basic mechanicals with the De Soto, but featured special styling.
[src:dodge-magnum/1958-dodge] The Coronet lasted through the 1959 model years.
[src:dodge-magnum/1958-dodge] This was the only line to feature the 230 in3 (3.8 L) *Getaway* I6 with 123 hp (92 kW), but the 325 in3 (5.3 L) *Red Ram (2bbl)/Super Red Ram (4bbl)* V8 was an option.
[src:dodge-magnum/1958-dodge] Coronets may typically be identified by a script mounted at the trailing edge of the belt-line stainless steel trim strip and a plain "up-sweep" molding of the rear fin trim, where both Royal and Custom Royal had a "dipping" element to the up-sweep trim.
[src:dodge-magnum/1958-dodge] Fin cap inserts were painted with a horizontally ribbed pattern.
[src:dodge-magnum/1958-dodge] Body styles offered were club sedan, sedan, two-door hardtop (Lancer), four-door hardtop (Lancer), and two-door convertible (Lancer).
[src:dodge-magnum/1958-dodge] Lancers were further identified by a lance and shield emblem on each fin.
[src:dodge-magnum/1958-dodge] Fin cap inserts were anodized with a horizontally ribbed pattern.
[src:dodge-magnum/1958-dodge] Body styles offered were sedan, two-door hardtop (Lancer), and four-door hardtop (Lancer).
[src:dodge-magnum/1958-dodge] It came with the 350 in3 (5.7 L) Ram Fire V8 with a standard two-barrel carburetor, but the optional four-barrel carburetor delivered 300 hp (224 kW).
[src:dodge-magnum/1958-dodge] A feature of the Custom Royal was its bumper-mounted exhaust ports which were only available on the Royal and Coronet models as part of the D-500 options.
[src:dodge-magnum/1958-dodge] Identifying exterior characteristics include Custom Royal script at the trailing edge of the belt-line molding, the pronounced check-mark, gold anodized Dodge block letters on the hood, and gold anodized Dodge script on the passenger side of the trunk.
[src:dodge-magnum/1958-dodge] Fin cap inserts were anodized and had a unique rectangular pattern.
[src:dodge-magnum/1958-dodge] All Custom Royals included a stainless molding above the bumper, on the flat edge below the trunk opening.
[src:dodge-magnum/1958-dodge] Body styles offered were sedan, two-door hardtop (Lancer), four-door hardtop (Lancer), and two-door convertible (Lancer).
[src:dodge-magnum/1958-dodge] To combat the recession of 1958, the Chrysler Corporation developed a program of spring specials to present a mid-year trim change on most of its makes.
[src:dodge-magnum/1958-dodge] The factory-produced spring specials for Dodge included a new wide, full-length belt line molding, grille emblem, fin end-caps, and a wide license plate escutcheon.
[src:dodge-magnum/1958-dodge] The Chrysler Corporation also shipped out all of these trim items individually to dealers so the dealers could "freshen up" the cars sitting on their lots.
[src:dodge-magnum/1958-dodge] Dealer-installed spring specials often include some elements of the factory spring special trim, but not always all.
[src:dodge-magnum/1958-dodge] New exterior colors introduced for spring were Poppy Red, Frosted Turquoise, and Paris Rose.
[src:dodge-magnum/1958-dodge] Unrelated to spring specials, Dodge changed the headlight trim midway through the production run.
[src:dodge-magnum/1958-dodge] Later cars have a wide lower edge to the headlight trim while early cars have a thin lower edge.
[src:dodge-magnum/1958-dodge] Trying to boost sales, the **Regal Lancer** model was added in February and only available as a two-door hardtop with special colors, exterior trim and interior.
[src:dodge-magnum/1958-dodge] Four color combinations were available: bronze with white trim, bronze with black trim, black with bronze trim, and white with bronze trim.
[src:dodge-magnum/1958-dodge] It featured special nameplates at the front of the side spear trim and heavy eyebrow trim.
[src:dodge-magnum/1958-dodge] Inside, Regal Lancers got their own interior with unique trim and door panels featuring molded armrests.
[src:dodge-magnum/1958-dodge] A bronze instrument panel with textured aluminum inserts was a Regal Lancer exclusive.
[src:dodge-magnum/1958-dodge] The standard engine offered for Regal Lancers was the 350 cubic inch displacement "Ram Fire" V8.
[src:dodge-magnum/1958-dodge] Optional engine choices were the 361 cubic inch displacement **D-500** and **Super D-500** iterations.
[src:dodge-magnum/1958-dodge] The Suburban was Dodge's two-door station wagon in 1958.
[src:dodge-magnum/1958-dodge] All station wagons came standard with the 350 Ram Fire engine.
[src:dodge-magnum/1958-dodge] The entry level four-door station wagon in 1958 was the Sierra.
[src:dodge-magnum/1958-dodge] Sierras came in either the six-passenger seat configuration or the nine-passenger "Spectator" seat configuration.
[src:dodge-magnum/1958-dodge] From the exterior the nine-passenger configuration can be easily identified by the spare tire panel behind the rear wheel opening and the rubber step-spots on the rear bumper.
[src:dodge-magnum/1958-dodge] Custom Sierra wagons were the top-of-the-line station wagon offering for Dodge.
[src:dodge-magnum/1958-dodge] As with Sierras, they were available as either six-passenger or Spectators.
[src:dodge-magnum/1958-dodge] The D-500 engine option was available across all models and all body styles including station wagons and the Regal Lancer.
[src:dodge-magnum/1958-dodge] The D-500 family of engines includes a four-barrel option, a dual four-barrel (Super D-500), and a Bendix electronic fuel injection system for the Super D-500.
[src:dodge-magnum/1958-dodge] The Bendix E.F.I. system proved to be troublesome and what few examples were built were recalled to be fitted with the normally aspirated dual four-barrel carburetor system.
[src:dodge-magnum/1958-dodge] On passenger cars, the D-500 emblem was located on the driver side of the trunk.
[src:dodge-magnum/1958-dodge] On station wagons, the D-500 emblem was located below the tail gate latch.
[src:dodge-magnum/1958-dodge] The 1958 D-500 emblem was unique to that year.
[src:dodge-magnum/1958-dodge] All D-500s came with bumper mounted exhaust ports.
[src:dodge-magnum/1958-dodge] The California Highway patrol was so impressed with the performance of the new Dodge they ordered 200 vehicles with the D-500 option to be used on patrol duty.
[src:dodge-magnum/1958-dodge] This was Chrysler's first move into specialized Police cars, and its success paved the way for decades of special police packages.
[src:dodge-magnum/1958-dodge] Dodge also offered a D-500-1 that was strictly for racing.
[src:dodge-magnum/1958-dodge] It set several speed records on the sand at Daytona and the salt flats at Bonneville.
[src:dodge-magnum/1958-dodge] They were also designed for NASCAR and drag racing.
[src:dodge-magnum/1958-dodge] The D-500-1 package was only available in a Coronet hardtop, convertible or two-door sedan with a manual transmission.
[src:dodge-magnum/1958-dodge] Apart from the spring specials, Dodge offered a variety of paint and trim schemes for 1958.
[src:dodge-magnum/1958-dodge] The monotone, basic, and deluxe two-tones all used the "short" belt-line trim with model script behind the trailing edge.
[src:dodge-magnum/1958-dodge] The saddle two-tone used the 1957 full-length belt-line trim and placed the model script below the front fender belt-line trim.
[src:dodge-magnum/1958-dodge] The Regal Lancer had paint and trim unique to that model.
[src:dodge-magnum/5g-tronic] This fourth-generation transmission by Mercedes-Benz replaced the older 4-speed 4G-Tronic transmission-family and its 5-speed derivative, and was replaced by the much more complex and costly 7-speed Mercedes-Benz 7G-Tronic transmission (model **W7A 700** · type **722.9**) introduced in 2003.
[src:dodge-magnum/5g-tronic] Due to its high torque capacity and lower cost, it was retained for turbocharged V8 and V12 engines, 4-cylinder applications and commercial vehicles for almost a decade.
[src:dodge-magnum/5g-tronic] Production ended in 2020 with niche applications like Sprinter with petrol/CNG M111 engine and Jeep Wrangler.
[src:dodge-magnum/5g-tronic] Activated by a toggle switch, Winter mode sets the gearbox to start off in 2nd gear, both in Drive and Reverse.
[src:dodge-magnum/5g-tronic] This is designed to reduce wheelspin on icy surfaces.
[src:dodge-magnum/5g-tronic] Also in "W" mode the transmission will shift at lower speeds.
[src:dodge-magnum/5g-tronic] "S" mode is not sport but Sommer (German for summer) or Standard.
[src:dodge-magnum/5g-tronic] With Jaguar XJR applications the switch is labeled "Sport." In regular driving mode the gearbox starts off in 2nd gear, both in Drive and Reverse, and will only engage 1st gear when triggered via the kickdown switch (Drive only).
[src:dodge-magnum/5g-tronic] While "Sport" mode is enabled the gearbox will always start off in 1st gear.
[src:dodge-magnum/5g-tronic] Speedshift is a performance feature set for the Mercedes-Benz transmissions which includes manual mode and active downshifting.
[src:dodge-magnum/5g-tronic] When cornering at high speed, the transmission maintains the same gear above a certain lateral acceleration level.
[src:dodge-magnum/5g-tronic] It can also automatically downshift before overtaking.
[src:dodge-magnum/5g-tronic] It was first used in 2001 Mercedes-Benz C 32 AMG and 2001 Mercedes-Benz SLK 32 AMG.
[src:dodge-magnum/5g-tronic] A version with mechanical lock-up of the torque converter from first gear and steering-wheel-mounted shifter.
[src:dodge-magnum/5g-tronic] AMG Speedshift is also used in 7G-Tronic transmission.
[src:dodge-magnum/5g-tronic] It was first used in 2002 Mercedes-Benz E 55 AMG, S 55 AMG, C55, CL 55 AMG.
[src:dodge-magnum/5g-tronic] A version used in Mercedes-Benz SLR McLaren.
[src:dodge-magnum/5g-tronic] The **5G-Tronic** is an electronically shifted 5-speed overdrive automatic transmission with torque converter lock-up, typically in gears 3, 4 and 5.
[src:dodge-magnum/5g-tronic] The main objective in replacing the predecessor model was to improve vehicle fuel economy with extra speeds and a wider gear span to allow the engine speed level to be lowered (downspeeding), which is a decisive factor in improving energy efficiency and thus reducing fuel consumption.
[src:dodge-magnum/5g-tronic] In addition, the lower engine speed level improves the noise-vibration-harshness comfort and the exterior noise is reduced.
[src:dodge-magnum/5g-tronic] The need of 2 housings and 2 different controls turn out the **W5A 030** as the least economically designed automatic transmission ever manufactured for passenger cars.
[src:dodge-magnum/5g-tronic] This was only possible thanks to computer-aided design.
[src:dodge-magnum/5g-tronic] The 5G-Tronic is the 1st generation in which in-line epicyclic gearing have been combined with parallel epicyclic gearing.
[src:dodge-magnum/5g-tronic] The resulting progress is reflected in an even better ratio between the number of gears and the number of components used compared to all layouts previously used by Mercedes-Benz.
[src:dodge-magnum/5g-tronic] That is why Mercedes-Benz refers to them as **NAG 1 (N**ew **A**utomatic Gearbox **G**eneration, starting with type 722.6 as generation **1**).
[src:dodge-magnum/5g-tronic] With 9 main components, it saves 2 components compared to the W5A 030.
[src:dodge-magnum/5g-tronic] The most obvious flaw of the gearset concept is the second gear, which is clearly too short, but this affected all Mercedes-Benz transmissions, especially automatic transmissions.
[src:dodge-magnum/5g-tronic] The 7G-Tronic in 2003 was the first to remedy this situation.
[src:dodge-magnum/5g-tronic] As shown in the assessment table below, another drawback of the gearset concept is the significant reduction in speed increase in 5th gear.
[src:dodge-magnum/all-wheel-drive] An **all-wheel drive vehicle** (**AWD vehicle**) is one with a powertrain capable of providing power to all its wheels, whether full-time or on-demand.
[src:dodge-magnum/all-wheel-drive] Reflects one axle with one wheel capable of being powered.
[src:dodge-magnum/all-wheel-drive] Reflects two axles with one wheel on each capable of being powered.
[src:dodge-magnum/all-wheel-drive] Reflects two axles with both wheels on each capable of being powered.
[src:dodge-magnum/all-wheel-drive] Reflects three axles with both wheels on each capable of being powered.
[src:dodge-magnum/all-wheel-drive] Reflects four axles with both wheels on each capable of being powered.
[src:dodge-magnum/all-wheel-drive] The wheels are driven, but not dependent on a central mechanical power coupling.
[src:dodge-magnum/all-wheel-drive] In the context of hybrid and electric vehicles, the North American designation of 'all-wheel-drive' may differ.
[src:dodge-magnum/all-wheel-drive] In some hybrid vehicles, the combustion engine is only mechanically connected to the front wheels, while the rear wheels are powered independently by an electric motor; this may be marketed as *eAWD*.
[src:dodge-magnum/all-wheel-drive] Furthermore, many electric vehicles have individual, unconnected motors powering each axle, or even each individual wheel, also without any center differential.
[src:dodge-magnum/all-wheel-drive] When tire grip is good during road driving, a differential is used between the axles to avoid driveline windup.
[src:dodge-magnum/all-wheel-drive] This is not required off-road, as the limited grip allows the tires to slip.
[src:dodge-magnum/all-wheel-drive] All-wheel drive vehicles designed for extensive off-road use may not have such a differential, and so they suffer from wind-up when used on-road.
[src:dodge-magnum/all-wheel-drive] Selectable 4WD also avoids this problem and requires only a simple dog clutch in the transfer case, rather than a differential.
[src:dodge-magnum/all-wheel-drive] For this reason, most early off-road vehicles used that system; e.g., Jeep, Land Rover.
[src:dodge-magnum/all-wheel-drive] As vehicles became more sophisticated and tires gave better winter performance in the 1960s, there was an interest in giving the benefits of all-wheel drive to conventional cars: not for off-road use but for winter use in snow and ice or on wet roads.
[src:dodge-magnum/all-wheel-drive] Exotic vehicles such as the high-powered Jensen FF followed by the AMC Eagle, Subaru Leone and Audi Quattro series were the first to offer all-wheel drive in a high-speed road-based car.
[src:dodge-magnum/all-wheel-drive] These, particularly the Quattro, would extensively develop this drivetrain with the use of viscous couplings and differentials to provide a safe and drivable car.
[src:dodge-magnum/all-wheel-drive] The first off-road / on-road hybrids such as the Range Rover also chose the permanent all-wheel-drive system rather than manual selection.
[src:dodge-magnum/automatic-transmission] An **automatic transmission** (**AT**) or **automatic gearbox** is a multi-speed transmission used in motor vehicles that does not require any input from the driver other than throttle position to change forward gears under normal driving conditions.
[src:dodge-magnum/automatic-transmission] The 1904 Sturtevant "horseless carriage gearbox" is often considered to be the first true automatic transmission.
[src:dodge-magnum/automatic-transmission] The first mass-produced automatic transmission was General Motors' Hydra-Matic, introduced in Oldsmobile models for the 1940 model year.
[src:dodge-magnum/automatic-transmission] Automatic transmissions are especially prevalent in vehicular drivetrains, particularly those subject to intense mechanical acceleration and frequent idle/transient operating conditions; commonly commercial/passenger/utility vehicles, such as buses and waste collection vehicles.
[src:dodge-magnum/automatic-transmission] Vehicles with internal combustion engines, unlike electric vehicles, require the engine to operate in a narrow range of rates of rotation, requiring a gearbox, operated manually or automatically, to drive the wheels over a wide range of speeds.
[src:dodge-magnum/automatic-transmission] Globally, 43% of new cars produced in 2015 were manual transmissions, falling to 37% by 2020.
[src:dodge-magnum/automatic-transmission] Automatic transmissions have long been prevalent in the United States, but only started to become common in Europe much later.
[src:dodge-magnum/automatic-transmission] In Europe in 1997, only 10–12% of cars had automatic transmissions.
[src:dodge-magnum/automatic-transmission] In 1957 over 80% of new cars in the United States had automatic transmissions.
[src:dodge-magnum/automatic-transmission] Automatic transmissions have been standard in large cars since at least 1974.
[src:dodge-magnum/automatic-transmission] By 2020 only 2.4% of new cars had manual transmissions.
[src:dodge-magnum/automatic-transmission] Historically, automatic transmissions were less efficient, but lower fuel prices in the US made this less of a problem than in Europe.
[src:dodge-magnum/automatic-transmission] In the United Kingdom, a majority of new cars have had automatic transmissions since 2020.
[src:dodge-magnum/automatic-transmission] Several manufacturers including Mercedes and Volvo no longer sell cars with manual transmissions.
[src:dodge-magnum/automatic-transmission] The growing prevalence of automatic transmissions is attributed to the increasing number of electric and hybrid cars, and the ease of integrating it with safety systems such as Autonomous Emergency Braking.
[src:dodge-magnum/automatic-transmission] The efficiency (power output as a percentage of input) of conventional automatic transmissions ranges from 86 to 94%.
[src:dodge-magnum/automatic-transmission] Manual transmissions are more fuel efficient than all but the newest automatic transmissions due to their inherently low parasitic losses (typically of about 4%) in addition to being cheaper to make, lighter, better performing, and of simpler mechanical design.
[src:dodge-magnum/automatic-transmission] Fuel economy worsens with lower efficiency.
[src:dodge-magnum/automatic-transmission] However, manual transmissions require the driver to operate the clutch and change gear whenever required.
[src:dodge-magnum/automatic-transmission] Real-world tests reported in 2022 found that in typical driving manual transmissions achieved 2 to 5% better fuel economy than automatics, increasing to 20% with an expert driver.
[src:dodge-magnum/automatic-transmission] Some laboratory tests show automatics in a better light due to the tests using a prescribed shifting pattern for manuals not always optimized for economy.
[src:dodge-magnum/automatic-transmission] However, on long highway journeys manual transmissions require maintaining a very specific cruising speed to optimise economy, making automatics preferable.
[src:dodge-magnum/automatic-transmission] The most common design of automatic transmissions is the hydraulic automatic, which typically uses planetary gearsets that are operated using hydraulics.
[src:dodge-magnum/automatic-transmission] The transmission is connected to the engine via a torque converter (or a fluid coupling prior to the 1960s), instead of the friction clutch used by most manual transmissions.
[src:dodge-magnum/automatic-transmission] A hydraulic automatic transmission uses planetary gearsets instead of the manual transmission's design of gears lined up along input, output and intermediate shafts.
[src:dodge-magnum/automatic-transmission] To change gears, the hydraulic automatic uses a combination of internal clutches, friction bands or brake packs.
[src:dodge-magnum/automatic-transmission] These devices are used to lock certain gears, thus setting which gear ratio is in use at a given time.
[src:dodge-magnum/automatic-transmission] A sprag clutch (a ratchet-like device which can freewheel and transmits torque in only one direction) is often used for routine gear shifts.
[src:dodge-magnum/automatic-transmission] The advantage of a sprag clutch is that it eliminates the sensitivity of timing a simultaneous clutch release/apply on two planetary gearsets, simply "taking up" the drivetrain load when actuated, and releasing automatically when the next gear's sprag clutch assumes the torque transfer.
[src:dodge-magnum/automatic-transmission] The friction bands are often used for manually selected gears (such as low range or reverse) and operate on the planetary drum's circumference.
[src:dodge-magnum/automatic-transmission] Bands are not applied when the drive/overdrive range is selected, the torque being transmitted by the sprag clutches instead.
[src:dodge-magnum/automatic-transmission] The aforementioned friction bands and clutches are controlled using automatic transmission fluid (ATF), which is pressurized by a pump and then directed to the appropriate bands/clutches to obtain the required gear ratio.
[src:dodge-magnum/automatic-transmission] The ATF provides lubrication, corrosion prevention, and a hydraulic medium to transmit the power required to operate the transmission.
[src:dodge-magnum/automatic-transmission] Made from petroleum with various refinements and additives, ATF is one of the few parts of the automatic transmission that needs routine service as the vehicle ages.
[src:dodge-magnum/automatic-transmission] The *main pump* which pressurises the ATF is typically a gear pump mounted between the torque converter and the planetary gear set.
[src:dodge-magnum/automatic-transmission] The input for the main pump is connected to the torque converter housing, which in turn is bolted to the engine's flexplate, so the pump provides pressure whenever the engine is running.
[src:dodge-magnum/automatic-transmission] The pressure of the ATF is regulated by a *governor* connected to the output shaft, which varies the pressure depending on the vehicle speed.
[src:dodge-magnum/automatic-transmission] The *valve body* inside the transmission is responsible for directing hydraulic pressure to the appropriate bands and clutches.
[src:dodge-magnum/automatic-transmission] It receives pressurized fluid from the main pump and consists of several spring-loaded valves, check balls, and servo pistons.
[src:dodge-magnum/automatic-transmission] In older automatic transmissions, the valves use the pump pressure and the pressure from a centrifugal governor on the output side (as well as other inputs, such as throttle position or the driver locking out the higher gears) to control which ratio is selected.
[src:dodge-magnum/automatic-transmission] As the vehicle and engine change speed, the difference between the pressures changes, causing different sets of valves to open and close.
[src:dodge-magnum/automatic-transmission] In more recent automatic transmissions, the valves are controlled by solenoids.
[src:dodge-magnum/automatic-transmission] These solenoids are computer-controlled, with the gear selection decided by a dedicated transmission control unit (TCU) or sometimes this function is integrated into the engine control unit (ECU).
[src:dodge-magnum/automatic-transmission] Modern designs have replaced the centrifugal governor with an electronic speed sensor that is used as an input to the TCU or ECU.
[src:dodge-magnum/automatic-transmission] Modern transmissions also factor in the amount of load on an engine at any given time, which is determined from either the throttle position or the amount of intake manifold vacuum.
[src:dodge-magnum/automatic-transmission] The multitude of parts, along with the complex design of the valve body, originally made hydraulic automatic transmissions much more expensive and time-consuming to build and repair than manual transmissions; however mass-production and developments over time have reduced this cost gap.
[src:dodge-magnum/automatic-transmission] To provide coupling and decoupling of the engine, a modern automatic transmission uses a torque converter instead of the friction clutch used in a manual transmission.
[src:dodge-magnum/automatic-transmission] The 1904 Sturtevant "horseless carriage gearbox" is often considered to be the first automatic transmission for motor vehicles.
[src:dodge-magnum/automatic-transmission] At higher engine speeds, high gear was engaged.
[src:dodge-magnum/automatic-transmission] As the vehicle slowed down and engine speed decreased, the gearbox would shift back to low.
[src:dodge-magnum/automatic-transmission] However, the transmission was prone to sudden failure, due to the transmission being unable to withstand forces from the abrupt gear changes.
[src:dodge-magnum/automatic-transmission] The adoption of planetary gearsets was a significant advance towards the modern automatic transmission.
[src:dodge-magnum/automatic-transmission] One of the first transmissions to use this design was the manual transmission fitted to the 1901–1904 Wilson-Pilcher automobile.
[src:dodge-magnum/automatic-transmission] This transmission was built in the United Kingdom and used two epicyclic gears to provide four gear ratios.
[src:dodge-magnum/automatic-transmission] A foot clutch was used for standing starts, gear selection was using a hand lever, helical gears were used (to reduce noise) and the gears used a constant-mesh design.
[src:dodge-magnum/automatic-transmission] A planetary gearset was also used in the 1908 Ford Model T, which was fitted with a two-speed manual transmission (without helical gears).
[src:dodge-magnum/automatic-transmission] An early patent for the automatic transmission was granted to Canadian inventor Alfred Horner Munro of Regina in 1923.
[src:dodge-magnum/automatic-transmission] Being a steam engineer, Munro designed his device to use compressed air rather than hydraulic fluid, and so it lacked power and never found commercial application.
[src:dodge-magnum/automatic-transmission] In 1923, a patent was approved in the United States describing the operation of a transmission where the manual shifting of gears and manual operation of a clutch was eliminated.
[src:dodge-magnum/automatic-transmission] Hoffman from Chicago and was titled: *Automatic Gear Shift and Speed Control*.
[src:dodge-magnum/automatic-transmission] However, it would be over a decade later until automatic transmissions were produced in significant quantities.
[src:dodge-magnum/automatic-transmission] In the meantime, several European and British manufacturers would use preselector gearboxes, a form of manual transmission which removed the reliance on the driver's skill to achieve smooth gear shifts.
[src:dodge-magnum/automatic-transmission] The first automatic transmission using hydraulic fluid was developed in 1932 by two Brazilian engineers, José Braz Araripe and Fernando Lehly Lemos.
[src:dodge-magnum/automatic-transmission] The evolution towards mass-produced automatic transmissions continued with the 1933–1935 REO Motor Car Company *Self-Shifter* semi-automatic transmission, which automatically shifted between two forward gears in the "Forward" mode (or between two shorter gear ratios in the "Emergency low" mode).
[src:dodge-magnum/automatic-transmission] Driver involvement was still required during normal driving, since standing starts required the driver to use the clutch pedal.
[src:dodge-magnum/automatic-transmission] This was followed in 1937 by the Oldsmobile *Automatic Safety Transmission*.
[src:dodge-magnum/automatic-transmission] Similar in operation to the REO *Self-Shifter*, the *Automatic Safety Transmission* shifted automatically between the two gear ratios available in the "Low" and "High" ranges and the clutch pedal was required for standing starts.
[src:dodge-magnum/automatic-transmission] The Chrysler *Fluid Drive*, introduced in 1939, was an optional addition to manual transmissions where a fluid coupling (similar to a torque-convertor, but without the torque multiplication) was added, to avoid the need to operate a manual clutch.
[src:dodge-magnum/automatic-transmission] The General Motors Hydra-Matic became the first mass-produced automatic transmission following its introduction in 1939 (1940 model year).
[src:dodge-magnum/automatic-transmission] Available as an option in cars such as the Oldsmobile Series 60 and Cadillac Sixty Special, the Hydra-Matic combined a fluid coupling with three hydraulically controlled planetary gearsets to produce four forward speeds plus reverse.
[src:dodge-magnum/automatic-transmission] The transmission was sensitive to engine throttle position and road speed, producing fully automatic up- and down-shifting that varied according to operating conditions.
[src:dodge-magnum/automatic-transmission] During World War II, the Hydra-Matic was used in some military vehicles.
[src:dodge-magnum/automatic-transmission] The first automatic transmission to use a torque converter (instead of a fluid coupling) was the Buick Dynaflow, which was introduced for the 1948 model year.
[src:dodge-magnum/automatic-transmission] In normal driving, the Dynaflow used only the top gear, relying on the torque multiplication of the torque convertor at lower speeds.
[src:dodge-magnum/automatic-transmission] The Dynaflow was followed by the Packard Ultramatic in mid-1949 and the Chevrolet Powerglide for the 1950 model year.
[src:dodge-magnum/automatic-transmission] Each of these transmissions had only two forward speeds, relying on the converter for additional torque multiplication.
[src:dodge-magnum/automatic-transmission] In the early 1950s, BorgWarner developed a series of three-speed torque converter automatics for car manufacturers such as American Motors, Ford and Studebaker.
[src:dodge-magnum/automatic-transmission] Chrysler was late in developing its own true automatic, introducing the two-speed torque converter PowerFlite in 1953, and the three-speed TorqueFlite in 1956.
[src:dodge-magnum/automatic-transmission] The latter was the first to utilize the Simpson compound planetary gearset.
[src:dodge-magnum/automatic-transmission] In 1956, the General Motors Hydra-Matic (which still used a fluid coupling) was redesigned based around the use of two fluid couplings to provide smoother shifts.
[src:dodge-magnum/automatic-transmission] This transmission was called the *Controlled Coupling Hydra-Matic*, or "Jetaway" transmission.
[src:dodge-magnum/automatic-transmission] The original Hydra-Matic remained in production until the mid-1960s at GM, with the licensed Rolls-Royce Automatic transmission soldiering on until 1978 on the Rolls-Royce Phantom VI.
[src:dodge-magnum/automatic-transmission] In 1964, General Motors released a new transmission, the Turbo Hydramatic, a three-speed transmission which used a torque convertor.
[src:dodge-magnum/automatic-transmission] The Turbo Hydramatic was among the first to have the basic gear selections (*park*, *reverse*, *neutral*, *drive*, *low*) which became the standard gear selection used for several decades.
[src:dodge-magnum/automatic-transmission] By the late 1960s, most of the fluid-coupling two-speed and four-speed transmissions had disappeared in favor of three-speed units with torque converters.
[src:dodge-magnum/automatic-transmission] Also around this time, whale oil was removed from the automatic transmission fluid.
[src:dodge-magnum/automatic-transmission] During the 1980s, automatic transmissions with four gear ratios became increasingly common, and many were equipped with lock-up torque convertors in order to improve fuel economy.
[src:dodge-magnum/automatic-transmission] Electronics began to be more commonly used to control the transmission, replacing mechanical control methods such as spring-loaded valves in the valve body.
[src:dodge-magnum/automatic-transmission] Most systems use solenoids which are controlled by either the engine control unit, or a separate transmission control unit.
[src:dodge-magnum/automatic-transmission] This allows for more precise control of shift points, shift quality, lower shift times and manual control.
[src:dodge-magnum/automatic-transmission] The first five-speed automatic was the Jatco 5R01, introduced in 1989 by Nissan in the Cedric and Gloria, and was electronically controlled.
[src:dodge-magnum/automatic-transmission] The first six-speed automatic was the ZF 6HP26 transmission, which debuted in the 2002 BMW 7 Series (E65).
[src:dodge-magnum/automatic-transmission] The first seven-speed automatic was the Mercedes-Benz 7G-Tronic transmission, which debuted a year later.
[src:dodge-magnum/automatic-transmission] In 2007, the first eight-speed transmission to reach production was the Toyota AA80E transmission.
[src:dodge-magnum/automatic-transmission] The first nine-speed and ten-speed transmissions were the 2013 ZF 9HP transmission and 2017 *Toyota Direct Shift-10A* (used in the Lexus LC) respectively.
[src:dodge-magnum/automatic-transmission] The gear selector is the input by which the driver selects the operating mode of an automatic transmission.
[src:dodge-magnum/automatic-transmission] A few automobiles employed a lever on the instrument panel, such as the 1955 Chrysler Corporation cars, and notably, the Corvair.
[src:dodge-magnum/automatic-transmission] Some automatic transmissions, especially by General Motors from 1940 to 1964, used a layout with *reverse* as the bottom position (e.g.
[src:dodge-magnum/automatic-transmission] Many transmissions also include positions to restrict the gear selection to the lower gears and engages the engine brake.
[src:dodge-magnum/automatic-transmission] These positions are often labelled "L" (low gear), "S" (second gear) or the number of the highest gear used in that position (eg 3, 2 or 1).
[src:dodge-magnum/automatic-transmission] If these positions are engaged at a time when it would result in excessive engine speed, many modern transmissions disregard the selector position and remain in the higher gear.
[src:dodge-magnum/automatic-transmission] Many modern transmissions include modes to adjust the shift logic to prefer either power or fuel economy.
[src:dodge-magnum/automatic-transmission] "Sport" (also called "Power" or "Performance") modes cause gear shifts to occur at higher engine speeds, allowing higher acceleration.
[src:dodge-magnum/automatic-transmission] "Economy" (also called "Eco" or "Comfort") modes cause gear shifts to occur at lower engine speeds to reduce fuel consumption.
[src:dodge-magnum/automatic-transmission] Since the 1990s, systems to manually request a specific gear or an upshift/downshift have become more common.
[src:dodge-magnum/automatic-transmission] These *manumatic* transmissions offer the driver greater control over the gear selection that the traditional modes to restrict the transmission to the lower gears.
[src:dodge-magnum/automatic-transmission] Use of the manumatic functions are typically achieved either via paddles located beside the steering column, or "+" and "-" controls on the gear selector.
[src:dodge-magnum/automatic-transmission] Some cars offer drivers both methods to request a manual gear selection.
[src:dodge-magnum/automatic-transmission] A *continuously variable transmission* (CVT) can change seamlessly through a continuous (infinite) range of gear ratios, compared with other automatic transmissions that provide a limited number of gear ratios in fixed steps.
[src:dodge-magnum/automatic-transmission] The flexibility of a CVT with suitable control may allow the engine to operate at a constant angular velocity while the vehicle moves at varying speeds.
[src:dodge-magnum/automatic-transmission] CVTs are used in cars, tractors, UTVs, motor scooters, snowmobiles, and earthmoving equipment.
[src:dodge-magnum/automatic-transmission] The most common type of CVT uses two pulleys connected by a belt or chain.
[src:dodge-magnum/automatic-transmission] However, several other designs have also been used.
[src:dodge-magnum/automatic-transmission] A *dual-clutch transmission* (DCT, sometimes referred to as a *twin-clutch transmission*, or *double-clutch transmission*) uses two separate clutches for odd and even gear sets.
[src:dodge-magnum/automatic-transmission] The design is often similar to two separate manual transmissions with their respective clutches contained within one housing, and working as one unit.
[src:dodge-magnum/automatic-transmission] In most car and truck applications, the DCT functions as an automatic transmission, requiring no driver input to change gears.
[src:dodge-magnum/automatic-transmission] The first DCT to reach production was the *Easidrive* automatic transmission introduced on the 1961 *Hillman Minx* mid-size car.
[src:dodge-magnum/automatic-transmission] This was followed by various eastern European tractors through the 1970s (using manual operation via a single clutch pedal), then the *Porsche 962 C* racing car in 1985.
[src:dodge-magnum/automatic-transmission] The first DCT of the modern era was used in the 2003 *Volkswagen Golf R32*.
[src:dodge-magnum/automatic-transmission] Since the late 2000s, DCTs have become increasingly widespread, and have supplanted hydraulic automatic transmissions in various models of cars.
[src:dodge-magnum/automatic-transmission] Modern versions of these systems that are fully automatic in operation, such as *Selespeed* and *Easytronic*, require no driver input over gear changes or clutch operation.
[src:dodge-magnum/automatic-transmission] Semi-automatic versions require only partial driver input (i.e., the driver must change gears manually), while fully automatic versions require no manual driver input, whatsoever (TCU or ECU operates both the clutch system and gear shifts automatically).
[src:dodge-magnum/automatic-transmission] Modern automated manual transmissions (AMT) have their roots and origins in older clutchless manual transmissions that began to appear on mass-production automobiles in the early 1930s and 1940s, prior to the introduction of hydraulic automatic transmissions.
[src:dodge-magnum/automatic-transmission] These systems were designed to reduce the amount of clutch or gear shifter usage required by the driver.
[src:dodge-magnum/automatic-transmission] These devices were intended to reduce the difficulty of operating conventional unsynchronised manual transmissions ("crash gearboxes") that were commonly used at the time, especially in stop-start driving.
[src:dodge-magnum/automatic-transmission] An early example of this transmission was introduced with the Hudson Commodore in 1942, called *Drive-Master*.
[src:dodge-magnum/automatic-transmission] Another early example of this transmission system was introduced in the 1955 Citroën DS, which used a 4-speed *BVH* transmission.
[src:dodge-magnum/automatic-transmission] This semi-automatic transmission used an automated clutch, which was actuated using hydraulics.
[src:dodge-magnum/automatic-transmission] Gear selection also used hydraulics, however, the gear ratio needs to be manually selected by the driver.
[src:dodge-magnum/automatic-transmission] This system was nicknamed *Citro-Matic* in the U.S.
[src:dodge-magnum/automatic-transmission] The first modern AMTs were introduced by BMW and Ferrari in 1997, with their *SMG* and *F1* transmissions, respectively.
[src:dodge-magnum/automatic-transmission] Both systems used hydraulic actuators and electrical solenoids, and a designated transmission control unit (TCU) for the clutch and shifting, plus steering wheel-mounted paddle shifters, if the driver wanted to change gear manually.
[src:dodge-magnum/automatic-transmission] Modern fully automatic AMTs, such as *Selespeed* and *Easytronic*, have now been largely superseded and replaced by the increasingly widespread dual-clutch transmission design.
[src:dodge-magnum/automotive-design] The functional design and development of a modern motor vehicle is typically done by a large team from many different disciplines also included within automotive engineering, however, design roles are not associated with requirements for professional- or chartered-engineer qualifications.
[src:dodge-magnum/automotive-design] Automotive design in this context focuses primarily on developing the visual appearance or aesthetics of vehicles, while also becoming involved in the creation of product concepts.
[src:dodge-magnum/automotive-design] Automotive design as a professional vocation is practiced by designers who may have an art background and a degree in industrial design or in transportation design.
[src:dodge-magnum/automotive-design] For the terminology used in the field, see the glossary of automotive design.
[src:dodge-magnum/automotive-design] The task of the design team is usually split into three main aspects: exterior design, interior design, and color and trim design.
[src:dodge-magnum/automotive-design] Graphic design is also an aspect of automotive design; this is generally shared amongst the design team as the lead designer sees fit.
[src:dodge-magnum/automotive-design] The design focuses not only on the isolated outer shape of automobile parts, but concentrates on the combination of form and function, starting from the vehicle package.
[src:dodge-magnum/automotive-design] The aesthetic value will need to correspond to ergonomic functionality and utility features as well.
[src:dodge-magnum/automotive-design] Though not all the new vehicular gadgets are to be designated as factory standard items, some of them may be integral to determining the future course of any specific vehicular models.
[src:dodge-magnum/automotive-design] The design team(s) responsible for the exterior of the vehicle develops the proportions, shape, and surface details of the vehicle.
[src:dodge-magnum/automotive-design] Exterior design is first done by a series of manual sketches and digital drawings.
[src:dodge-magnum/automotive-design] Progressively, more detailed drawings are executed and approved by appropriate layers of management, followed by digital rendering to images.
[src:dodge-magnum/automotive-design] Consumer feedback is generally sought at this point to help iteratively refine vehicle concepts according to the targeted market and will continue throughout the rest of the design refinement process.
[src:dodge-magnum/automotive-design] After more progressive refinement, industrial plasticine and or digital models are developed from and along with the drawings and images.
[src:dodge-magnum/automotive-design] The data from these models are then used to create quarter-scale and finally full-sized mock-ups of the final design.
[src:dodge-magnum/automotive-design] With three- and five-axis CNC milling machines, the clay model is first designed in a computer program and then "carved" using the machine and large amounts of clay.
[src:dodge-magnum/automotive-design] Even in times of photorealistic (three-dimensional) software and virtual models on power walls, the clay model is still the most important tool for a final evaluation of the exterior design of a vehicle and, therefore, is used throughout the industry.
[src:dodge-magnum/automotive-design] The designer responsible for the vehicles' interior develops the proportions, shape, placement, and surfaces for the instrument panel, seats, door trim panels, headliner, pillar trims, etc.
[src:dodge-magnum/automotive-design] Here the emphasis is on ergonomics and the comfort of the passengers.
[src:dodge-magnum/automotive-design] The procedure here is the same as with exterior design (sketch, digital model, and clay model).
[src:dodge-magnum/automotive-design] The color and trim (or color and materials) designer is responsible for the research, design, and development of all interior and exterior colors and materials used on a vehicle.
[src:dodge-magnum/automotive-design] These include paints, plastics, fabric designs, leather, grains, carpet, headliner, wood trim, and so on.
[src:dodge-magnum/automotive-design] Color, contrast, texture, and pattern must be carefully combined to give the vehicle a unique interior environment experience.
[src:dodge-magnum/automotive-design] Designers work closely with exterior and interior designers.
[src:dodge-magnum/automotive-design] Designers draw inspiration from other design disciplines such as industrial design, fashion, home furnishing, architecture, and sometimes product design.
[src:dodge-magnum/automotive-design] Specific research is done into global trends to design for projects two to three model years in the future.
[src:dodge-magnum/automotive-design] Trend boards are created from this research to keep track of design influences as they relate to the automotive industry.
[src:dodge-magnum/automotive-design] The designer then uses this information to develop themes and concepts that are then further refined and tested on the vehicle models.
[src:dodge-magnum/automotive-design] The design team also develops graphics for items, such as badges, decals, dials, switches, kick or tread strips, or liveries.
[src:dodge-magnum/automotive-design] The sketches and rendering are transformed into 3D digital surface modeling and rendering for real-time evaluation with Math data in the initial stages.
[src:dodge-magnum/automotive-design] During the development process succeeding phases will require the 3D model fully developed to meet the aesthetic requirements of a designer as well as all engineering and manufacturing requirements.
[src:dodge-magnum/automotive-design] The fully developed CAS digital model will be re-developed for manufacturing meeting the Class-A surface standards that involve both technical as well as aesthetics.
[src:dodge-magnum/automotive-design] A Product Engineering team will further develop this data.
[src:dodge-magnum/automotive-design] These modelers usually have a background in industrial design or sometimes tooling engineering in the case of some Class-A modelers.
[src:dodge-magnum/automotive-design] Autodesk Alias and ICEM Surf are the two most widely used software tools for Class-A development.
[src:dodge-magnum/automotive-design] Uniform surface continuity is critical to ensure Class-A surface standards.
[src:dodge-magnum/automotive-design] The continuity of the areas is between the quality grades G0 through G3, with G3 guaranteeing the cleanest patch-to-patch transitions.
[src:dodge-magnum/automotive-design] The design process occurs concurrently with other product engineers who will be engineering the styling data for meeting performance, manufacturing, and safety regulations.
[src:dodge-magnum/automotive-design] From mid-phase, back-and-forth interactions between the designers and product engineers culminate into a finished product being manufacturing-ready.
[src:dodge-magnum/automotive-design] Apart from this the engineering team parallelly works in the following areas.
[src:dodge-magnum/automotive-design] Product Engineering (Body In White Sheetmetal Design and Plastic engineering), NVH Development team, Prototype development, Powertrain engineering, Physical Vehicle validation, Tool and Die development, and Manufacturing process design.
[src:dodge-magnum/automotive-design] The design team for a specific model consists of a chief designer and an exterior as well as an interior designer.
[src:dodge-magnum/automotive-design] In some cases, all three roles are done by one designer.
[src:dodge-magnum/automotive-design] Several junior designers are involved in the development process as well and make specific contributions all overseen by the chief designer.
[src:dodge-magnum/automotive-design] Apart from this, the color and trim designer works closely with other designers.
[src:dodge-magnum/automotive-design] The clay model team and digital model team work closely with the styling team all located within the studio.
[src:dodge-magnum/automotive-design] Apart from this, there would be studio heads, studio managers, and prototype engineers who would work across all teams in the studio.
[src:dodge-magnum/automotive-design] The total team size for developing a full car usually ranges from 25 to 40 members and the development time lasts for more than 24 months until signed-off for tooling and production.
[src:dodge-magnum/automotive-design] After that, a smaller team would be working until the vehicle launch.
[src:dodge-magnum/automotive-design] In the early days of the automobile, manufacturers prioritized function over form, focusing on building simple, reliable, and affordable vehicles.
[src:dodge-magnum/automotive-design] Some automakers began incorporating artists to combine styling with engineering.
[src:dodge-magnum/automotive-design] Visual appeal remained secondary to technical and safety advancements until the 1930s, an era that, despite its financial challenges, became a high point of creative coachbuilding.
[src:dodge-magnum/automotive-design] World War II halted the momentum, but it evolved when the industry restarted in the late 1940s, heavily influenced by the Jet Age.
[src:dodge-magnum/automotive-design] However, the artwork and models created by designers are routinely destroyed so as not to be seen by competing automakers.
[src:dodge-magnum/automotive-design] Great car designers are visionary artists who can translate their ideas from sketches and models into tangible vehicles.
[src:dodge-magnum/automotive-design] Their work is a blend of artistry and engineering, shaped by collaborations with engineers who help bring their creative concepts to life.
[src:dodge-magnum/automotive-design] Some automobile forms have served to influence the success and careers of successive designers.
[src:dodge-magnum/automotive-design] In the United States, automotive design reached a turning point in the 1920s when the American national automobile market began reaching saturation.
[src:dodge-magnum/automotive-design] To maintain unit sales, General Motors head Alfred P.
[src:dodge-magnum/automotive-design] Sloan Jr. suggested annual model-year design changes to convince car owners that they needed to buy a new replacement each year, an idea borrowed from the bicycle industry (though Sloan usually gets the credit or blame).
[src:dodge-magnum/automotive-design] Critics called his strategy planned obsolescence.
[src:dodge-magnum/automotive-design] Sloan preferred the term "dynamic obsolescence".
[src:dodge-magnum/automotive-design] This strategy had far-reaching effects on the auto business, the field of product design, and eventually the American economy.
[src:dodge-magnum/automotive-design] The smaller automakers could not maintain the pace and expense of yearly re-styling.
[src:dodge-magnum/automotive-design] Henry Ford did not like the model-year change because he clung to an engineer's notions of simplicity, the economics of scale, and design integrity.
[src:dodge-magnum/automotive-design] GM surpassed Ford's sales in 1931 and became the dominant company in the industry thereafter.
[src:dodge-magnum/automotive-design] The frequent design changes also made it necessary to use a body-on-frame rather than the lighter but less adaptable monocoque design used by most European automakers.
[src:dodge-magnum/automotive-design] In the 1930s, Chrysler's innovations with aerodynamics helped launch the Chrysler Airflow in 1934, which was revolutionary and radical compared to contemporary vehicles.
[src:dodge-magnum/automotive-design] However, inadequate consumer acceptance of the advanced appearance of the cars forced a re-design of succeeding models of the Airflow.
[src:dodge-magnum/automotive-design] This marketing experience made the entire industry take note of the high risks involved in incorporating major design advancements into their production cars.
[src:dodge-magnum/automotive-design] A major influence on American auto styling and marketing was Harley Earl, who is credited with inventing the idea of a concept car, and who brought the tailfin and other aeronautical design references to auto design starting with the rear fenders of the 1948 Cadillac.
[src:dodge-magnum/automotive-design] Another notable designer was Chrysler group's designer Virgil Exner, who developed the Forward look design in the mid-1950s.
[src:dodge-magnum/automotive-design] Exner is also credited with using wind tunnel testing to justify incorporating tailfins, thus moving the company away from boxy-looking cars into more aerodynamic and futuristic designs that were influenced by rockets after WWII.
[src:dodge-magnum/automotive-design] Other influential automotive designers include Raymond Loewy, who was responsible for a number of Studebaker vehicles such as the Avanti, and Gordon Buehrig, who was responsible for the Auburn 851, as well as the Cord 810 and 812.
[src:dodge-magnum/automotive-design] Starting in the 1960s, Dick Teague, who spent most of his career with American Motors Corporation (AMC), originated the concept of using interchangeable body panels so as to create a wide array of different vehicles using the same stampings, starting with the AMC Cavalier.
[src:dodge-magnum/automotive-design] Teague was responsible for automotive designs such as the two-seat AMC AMX muscle car, the subcompact Gremlin, the Pacer, and Matador coupe, as well as the original and market segment-creating, Jeep Cherokee.
[src:dodge-magnum/automotive-design] Additionally during the 1960s, Ford's first-generation Ford Mustang and Thunderbird marked another era leading into new market segments from Detroit.
[src:dodge-magnum/automotive-design] The Ford Mustang achieved record sales in its first year of production and established the pony car segment.
[src:dodge-magnum/automotive-design] Personal injury litigation has affected the design and appearance of the car in the 20th century.
[src:dodge-magnum/automotive-design] Until World War I, most automakers were concerned with mechanical reliability rather than the external appearance of their cars.
[src:dodge-magnum/automotive-design] Later, luxury and aesthetics became a demand, and also an effective marketing tool.
[src:dodge-magnum/automotive-design] Designs from each nation with their own strong cultural identity are reflected in their exterior and interior designs.
[src:dodge-magnum/automotive-design] World War II slowed the progress, but after the early 1950s, Italian designers set the trend and remained the driving force until the early part of the 1980s.
[src:dodge-magnum/automotive-design] In France notable designs came from Bugatti and Avions Voisin.
[src:dodge-magnum/automotive-design] Of the mass-selling cars, Citroën launched their vehicles with innovative designs and engineering, aided by the styling of Flaminio Bertoni as evident from the Citroën DS.
[src:dodge-magnum/automotive-design] After World War II, with the decline of the coachbuilding industry, French automakers (except Citroën) followed British and other popular trends until they gained financial stability.
[src:dodge-magnum/automotive-design] During the 1980s, manufacturers like Renault cultivated their own strong design identities with designers like Patrick Le Quément.
[src:dodge-magnum/automotive-design] Peugeot, which was dependent on Pininfarina since the early post-war period, later established its own brand identity from the 1980s onwards.
[src:dodge-magnum/automotive-design] Its other company, Citroën, still retains its distinctive French innovations for its designs.
[src:dodge-magnum/automotive-design] Great Britain was Europe's leading manufacturer of automobiles until the late-1960s.
[src:dodge-magnum/automotive-design] During that era, there were more British-based automakers than in the rest of Europe combined.
[src:dodge-magnum/automotive-design] The British automobile industry catered to all segments ranging from compact, budget, sports, utility, and luxury-type cars.
[src:dodge-magnum/automotive-design] Car design in Britain was markedly different from other European designs largely because British designers were not influenced by other European art or design movements, as well as the British clay modelers, used a different sweep set.
[src:dodge-magnum/automotive-design] British cars until World War II were sold in most of the British colonies.
[src:dodge-magnum/automotive-design] Innovations in vehicle packaging and chassis engineering combined with global familiarity with British designs meant vehicles were acceptable to public tastes at that time.
[src:dodge-magnum/automotive-design] British skilled resources such as panel beaters, die machinists, and clay modelers were also available partly due to their involvement with the motorsport industry.
[src:dodge-magnum/automotive-design] Still, during the 1960s, British manufacturers sought professional help from Italian designers and studios such as Giovanni Michelotti, Ercole Spada, and Pininfarina.
[src:dodge-magnum/automotive-design] Notable British contributions to automobile designs were the Morris Mini by Alec Issigonis, several Jaguar Cars by Sir William Lyons and Malcolm Sayer, Aston Martin DB Series, and several cars from Triumph and MG.
[src:dodge-magnum/automotive-design] Ford Europe, based in Great Britain, is notable for the Ford Sierra line, a work of Uwe Bahnsen, Robert Lutz, and Patrick le Quément.
[src:dodge-magnum/automotive-design] Other notable British designers include William Towns for Aston Martin, and David Bache for Land Rover and Range Rover, and Ian Callum for Jaguar.
[src:dodge-magnum/automotive-design] During the complex changes in the British car industry in the 1990s and beyond, a mix of designers worked on all of the remaining mainstream brands under one design director and in one studio.
[src:dodge-magnum/automotive-design] The director most involved was Geoff Upex, with his team of Richard Woolley, Dave Saddington, George Thomson, Alan Mobberley, and Martin Peach (colour and trim).
[src:dodge-magnum/automotive-design] Germany is often considered the birthplace of industrial design with the Bauhaus School of Design, before it was closed down by the Nazi regime.
[src:dodge-magnum/automotive-design] Ferdinand Porsche and his family played a significant role in German design.
[src:dodge-magnum/automotive-design] Mercedes-Benz passenger cars were also in the luxury segment and played an important role in German car design.
[src:dodge-magnum/automotive-design] After the 1980s, German design evolved into a distinctive Teutonic style often to complement their highly engineered cars suited to Autobahns.
[src:dodge-magnum/automotive-design] The early German design clues of the present-day owe some part to Italian designers like Giovanni Michelotti, Ercole Spada, Bruno Sacco, and Giorgetto Giugiaro.
[src:dodge-magnum/automotive-design] During the mid- and late-20th century one of the most influential coach builders/designers in Germany was Karmann.
[src:dodge-magnum/automotive-design] German designs started gaining popularity after the 1980s, notable after the formation of Audi.
[src:dodge-magnum/automotive-design] Volkswagen, which was dependent on Marcello Gandini, Giorgetto Giugiaro, and Karmann, later formed the contemporary design language along with Audi.
[src:dodge-magnum/automotive-design] BMW entered the automobile design with sporty-looking everyday sedans using Giovanni Michelotti.
[src:dodge-magnum/automotive-design] These models were later enhanced by Ercole Spada into the 1980s, and Klaus Luthe until the mid-1990s.
[src:dodge-magnum/automotive-design] The American-born designer Chris Bangle was hired by BMW in the late-1990s to redefine the brand.
[src:dodge-magnum/automotive-design] Bangle incorporated new single-press technology for compound curves to add controversial styling elements to his designs.
[src:dodge-magnum/automotive-design] The Porsche family contribution was instrumental in the evolution of Porsche cars, while the Italian designer Bruno Sacco helped create various Mercedes Models from the 1960s to the 1990s.
[src:dodge-magnum/automotive-design] In Italy, Fiat and Alfa Romeo played a major role in car design.
[src:dodge-magnum/automotive-design] Many coachbuilders were dependent on these two major manufacturers.
[src:dodge-magnum/automotive-design] Italian manufacturers had a large presence in motorsports leading to several sport car manufacturers like Ferrari, Lancia, Lamborghini, Maserati, etc.
[src:dodge-magnum/automotive-design] During the late-1950s, Italian automobile designs gained global popularity coinciding with the modern fashion and architecture at that time around the world.
[src:dodge-magnum/automotive-design] Various design and technical schools in Turin turned out designers on a large scale.
[src:dodge-magnum/automotive-design] By the late-1960s, almost all Italian coachbuilders transformed into design studios catering to automakers around the world.
[src:dodge-magnum/automotive-design] The trend continued in the 1990s when the Japanese and Korean manufacturers sourced designs from these styling studios.
[src:dodge-magnum/automotive-design] Some Italian designers whose design services were sought globally include Aldo Brovarone, Giovanni Michelotti, Ercole Spada, Bruno Sacco, Marcello Gandini, Giorgetto Giugiaro, and Walter de Silva.
[src:dodge-magnum/automotive-design] Sweden had Volvo and Saab as domestic automakers, and the nation's northern location required that cars needed to withstand Nordic climate conditions.
[src:dodge-magnum/automotive-design] The Scandinavian design elements are known for their minimalism and simplicity.
[src:dodge-magnum/automotive-design] One of the early original Scandinavian designs was the Saab 92001 by Sixten Sason and Gunnar Ljungström.
[src:dodge-magnum/automotive-design] Koenigsegg, founded in the 1990s, became Sweden's first domestic producer of high end sports cars, with many of their models featuring in house designs by Swedish designers.
[src:dodge-magnum/automotive-design] Before World War II and until the early-1990s, Czechoslovakia had a strong presence in the automotive industry with manufacturers like Škoda, Jawa, Tatra, CZ, Praga, and Zetor.
[src:dodge-magnum/automotive-design] Czech automobiles were generally known for their originality in mechanical simplicity and designs were remarkably Bohemian as evident from Tatra cars and Jawa motorcycles.
[src:dodge-magnum/automotive-design] During the Communist regime, the design started falling back and ultimately the domestic automakers ended up as subsidiaries of EU-based companies.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] Named after the town of Brampton in Cumberland, England, Brampton was incorporated as a village in 1853 and as a town in 1873, and became a city in 1974.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] The modern City of Brampton was formed following an amalgamation of several surrounding townships and communities.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] The city was once known as "The Flower Town of Canada", a title referring to its abundance of greenhouses and strong floriculture industry in the 1860s.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] It maintains the term "Flower City" as its slogan.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] Despite being built as a car-centric city, Brampton has a significant transit system, with a ridership of 49,200,800, or about 226,500 per weekday as of the second quarter of 2024.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] Before the arrival of British settlers, the Mississaugas of the Credit First Nation held 648,000 acres (262,000 ha) of the land north to the head of the Lake Purchase lands and extending to the unceded territory of the Chippewa of Lakes Huron and Simcoe.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] European settlers began to arrive in the area in the late 18th century.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] In October 1818, the chief of the Mississaugas of the Credit First Nation signed Treaty 19, also known as the Ajetance Purchase, surrendering the area to the British Crown.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] Prior to the 1830s, most business in Chinguacousy Township took place at Martin Salisbury's tavern.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] One mile from the corner of Hurontario Street and the 5th Sideroad (now Main and Queen Streets in the centre of Brampton), William Buffy's tavern was the only significant building.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] At the time, the intersection was referred to as "Buffy's Corners".
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] By 1834, John Elliott laid out the area in lots for sale, calling it "Brampton", which was soon adopted by others.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] In 1853, a small agricultural fair was set up by the newly initiated County Agricultural Society of the County of Peel and was held at the corner of Main and Queen streets.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] Grains, produce, roots, and dairy products were up for sale.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] Horses and cattle, along with other lesser livestock, were also sold at the market.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] This agricultural fair eventually became the modern Brampton Fall Fair.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] In that same year, Brampton was incorporated as a village.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] In 1866, the town became the county seat and the location of the Peel County Courthouse which was built in 1865–66; a three-storey County jail was added at the rear in 1867.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] Edward Dale, an immigrant from Dorking, England, established a flower nursery in Brampton shortly after his arrival in 1863.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] Dale's Nursery had become the town's largest and most prominent employer, developed a flower grading system, and established a global export market for its products.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] The company chimney was a town landmark, until Brampton Town Council allowed it to be torn down in 1977.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] At its height, the company had 140 greenhouses, and was the largest cut flower business in North America, producing 20 million blooms and introducing numerous rose and orchid cultivar to the market.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] It also spurred the development of other nurseries in the town.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] Forty-eight hothouse flower nurseries once did business in the town.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] In January 1867, Peel County separated from the County of York, a union which had existed since 1851.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] By 1869, Brampton had a population of 1,800.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] The town of Brampton had problems with inadequate water supply in its early years, as the town relied on shallow wells for not just residential water, but commercial use and fire-fighting.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] A Brampton Water Works filtration plant was built south of the lake, located where present-day White Spruce Park is.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] Today the city uses water from other sources, and Heart Lake is now the centerpiece of Heart Lake Conservation Area.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] A federal grant had enabled the village to found its first public library in 1887, which included 360 volumes from the Mechanic's Institute (established in 1858).
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] In 1907, the library received a grant from the Carnegie Foundation, set up by United States steel magnate and philanthropist Andrew Carnegie, to build a new, expanded library; it serves several purposes, featuring the Brampton Library.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] The Carnegie libraries were built on the basis of communities coming up with matching funds and guaranteeing maintenance.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] Gage (owner of Gage Publishing, a publishing house specializing in school textbooks) purchased a 3.25-acre (1.32 ha) portion of the gardens and lawns of the Alder Lea estate (now called Alderlea) that had been built on Main Street by Kenneth Chisholm in 1867 to 1870.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] (Chisholm, a merchant and founding father of Brampton, had been the Town reeve, then warden of Peel County, then MPP for Brampton and eventually, Registrar of Peel County.) Gage donated 1.7 acres (0.69 ha) of the property to the town, with a specific condition that it be made into a park.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] Citizens donated $1,054 and the town used the funds to purchase extra land to ensure a larger park.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] A group of regional farmers in Brampton had trouble getting insurance from city-based companies.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] After several meetings in Clairville Hall, they decided to found the County of Peel Farmers Mutual Fire Insurance Company.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] In 1955, when the company moved to its third and current location, 103 Queen Street West, it took the new name of Peel Mutual Insurance Company.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] It reigns as the longest-running company in modern Brampton.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] Harmsworth Decorating Centre was established in 1890, as Harmsworth and Son, operated out of the family's house on Queen Street West.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] The current location was purchased on September 1, 1904, after a fire destroyed their original store.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] Purchased for $1,400, the 24 Main Street South location is the longest-operating retail business in what is now Brampton.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] In 1963, the town established *The Flower Festival of Brampton*, which was based on the *Rose Festival* in Portland, Oregon, United States.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] It began to market itself as the *Flower Town of Canada*.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] In 1974, the two townships of Chinguacousy and Toronto Gore were incorporated into Brampton.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] In a revival of this theme, on June 24, 2002, the City Council established the "Flower City Strategy", to promote a connection to its flower-growing heritage.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] The intention was to inspire design projects and community landscaping to beautify the city, adopt a sustainable environmental approach, and to protect its natural and cultural heritage.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] The Rose Theatre was named in keeping with this vision and is to serve as a cultural institution in the city.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] In addition, the city participates in the national Communities in Bloom competition as part of that strategy.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] The Old Shoe Factory, located at 57 Mill Street North, once housed the Hewetson Shoe Company.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] It was listed as a historical property under the Ontario Heritage Act in 2008.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] Today it is occupied by various small businesses.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] The lobby and hallways retain details from 1907.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] Walls are decorated with pictures and artifacts of local Brampton history and old shoemaking equipment.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] A self-guided historical walking tour of downtown Brampton called "A Walk Through Time" is available at Brampton City Hall and online at no cost.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] Planned as an innovative "new town", Bramalea was developed in the 1950s immediately east of the Town of Brampton in Chinguacousy Township.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] He sold the land to Brampton Leasing (the former name of the developer) and built one of Bramalea's first houses on Dixie Road.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] The community was developed according to its detailed master plan, which included provisions for a parkland trail system and a "downtown" to include essential services and a shopping centre.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] The downtown's centrepiece was the Civic Centre, built in 1972 to include the city hall and library.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] Directly across Team Canada Drive, a shopping centre, Bramalea City Centre was built.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] These developments were connected by a long tunnel, planned to provide protection from winter weather.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] The tunnel has long since been closed due to safety issues.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] In 1974, the Ontario provincial government decided to update Peel County's structure.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] It amalgamated several towns and villages into the new City of Mississauga.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] While only Huttonville and Churchville still exist as identifiable communities, other names like Claireville are re-emerging as names of new developments.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] The province converted Peel County into the Regional Municipality of Peel.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] Brampton retained its role as the administrative centre of Peel Region, which it already had as county seat.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] The regional council chamber, the Peel Regional Police force, the public health department, and the region's only major museum, the Peel Art Gallery, Museum and Archives, are all located in Brampton.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] This change had its critics among those with a strong sense of local identities.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] Bramptonians feared urban sprawl would dissolve their town's personality.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] Bramalea residents took pride in the built-from-scratch and organised structure that had come with their new satellite city and did not want to give it up.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] Others in Bramalea accept they are part of Brampton, and they make up a "tri-city" area: the original Brampton, Heart Lake, Bramalea.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] In 1972, Chinguacousy built a new civic centre in Bramalea.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] Two years later, when Brampton and Chinguacousy merged, the new city's council was moved from its modest downtown Brampton locale to the Bramalea building.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] The library systems of Brampton and Chinguacousy were merged, resulting in a system of four locations.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] Some have questioned the future of Peel Region as encompassing all of Brampton, Mississauga, and Caledon.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] The Mississauga council, led by Mayor Hazel McCallion, voted to become a single-tier municipality and asked the provincial government to be separated from Peel Region.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] They argued the city has outgrown the need for a regional layer of government, and that Mississauga is being held back by supporting Brampton and Caledon with its municipal taxes.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] In the early 1980s, Cineplex Odeon closed the Capitol Theatre in Brampton.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] The City bought the facility in 1981 under the leadership of councillor Diane Sutter.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] It adapted the former vaudeville venue and movie house as a performing arts theatre, to be used also as a live music venue.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] Renovations and maintenance were expensive.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] In 1983, Toronto consultants Woods Gordon reported to the City that, rather than continue "pouring money" into the Heritage, they should construct a new 750-seat facility with up-to-date features.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] This recommendation was adopted, and the city designated the 2005–06 season as the Heritage Theatre's "grand finale" season.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] The city funded construction of the new Rose Theatre, which opened in September 2006.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] Carabram was founded in 1982, the result of volunteers from different ethnic communities wanting to organize a festival celebrating diversity and cross-cultural friendship.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] The name was loosely related to Toronto's Caravan Festival of Cultures.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] Carabram's first event featured Italian, Scots, Ukrainian, and West Indian pavilions.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] By 2003, the fair had 18 pavilions attracting 45,000 visitors.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] Brampton has grown to become one of the most diverse cities in Canada.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] In 1996, the city was 13% South Asian and 8.2% black.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] By 2016, the South Asian community grew significantly to represent 44.3% of the city's population, while the black population grew to 14%.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] Responding to a growing multi-cultural population, the Peel Board of Education introduced evening English as a Second Language (ESL) classes at high schools.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] Originally taught by volunteers, the classes eventually were scheduled as daytime courses taught by paid instructors.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] In the 1980s, the public and Catholic board expanded its language programs, offering night classes in 23 languages.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] These were introduced due to requests by parents, who wanted their children to learn their ancestral languages and heritage.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] In the late 1980s, Mayor Ken Whillans gained approval and funding for the construction of a new city hall in Brampton's downtown.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] The facility was designed by local architects and built on the site of a former bus terminal.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] Whillians did not get to see the opening of the new hall in June 1991 because of his death in August 1990.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] Its completion brought the municipal government back to downtown Brampton.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] The facility expanded in 2014 with the addition of a nine-storey tower at 41 George Street and is connected to the original building by a glass walkway called Heritage Way.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] In 1991, development of another new town, Springdale, began.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] In 1999, development started to appear as far north as the city's border with Caledon along Mayfield Road.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] The Region designated this border as the line of demarcation for urban development until 2021, although development already began spilling north of Mayfield in the late 2010s.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] Part of the boundary between Brampton and Vaughan is also nearly completely urbanized.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] Changes continue to reflect the growth of the city.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] In 1992 the City purchased the Brampton Fairgrounds, to be used for other development.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] The Agricultural Society relocated in 1997 outside the boundaries of the city to Heart Lake and Old School roads.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] Brampton's 2003 Sesquicentennial celebrations boosted community spirit, reviving the tradition of a summer parade (with 100 floats), and creating other initiatives.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] To commemorate the town's history, the city under Mayor Fennell reintroduced floral projects to the community.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] These have included more plantings around town, the revival in 2005 of the city Parade, and participation in the Canada Communities in Bloom project.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] Brampton has a total land area of 265 square kilometres (102 sq mi).
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] It follows the line as far east as the former Indian Line (today a private access road), turns back north along it to briefly border Toronto (Etobicoke), towards the intersection of Steeles Ave. and Albion Road/Highway 50.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] Brampton features a continental climate (Köppen climate classification: *Dfa*) which is typical of the rest of the Greater Toronto Area.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] Data from Toronto Pearson International Airport, located 10.55 km (6.56 mi) east.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] Data is from Georgetown, located 10.93 km (6.79 mi) south-southwest.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] In the 2021 Canadian census conducted by Statistics Canada, Brampton had a population of 656,480 living in 182,472 of its 189,086 total private dwellings, a change of 10.6% from its 2016 population of 593,638.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] At its growth rate of 10.6% since the 2016 census, Brampton was the fastest-growing of Canada's largest 25 municipalities.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] In the 2021 Canadian census, people of South Asian origin were the largest ethnocultural group in Brampton—accounting for 52.4% of the population.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] The city is ethnically diverse with approximately 60% of Brampton's residents being foreign-born.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] In 2021, the most reported religion among the population was Christianity (35.7%), with Catholicism (17.3%) making up the largest denomination.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] 10.3% of the population did not identify with a particular religion.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] The Toronto Ontario Temple for the Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints (LDS Church) is located in Brampton.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] The 2021 census found that English was the mother tongue of 42.9% of the population.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] Companies with headquarters in Brampton include MDA Space Missions, which will be building the CanadaArm 3.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] Loblaw Companies Ltd., Chrysler Canada Brampton Assembly Plant, Gamma-Dynacare Medical Laboratories, Mandarin Restaurant, Brita, Shoppers Drug Mart, Canon, Canadian Blood Services, Sleep Country Canada and Clorox.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] William Osler Health System employs approximately 5,000 at its Brampton Civic and Peel Memorial campuses.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] Lululemon, and Pet Valu have their main GTA distribution centres in the city.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] Wolseley Plumbing built a distribution Center and showroom in Brampton in 2024.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] Alstom has an assembly plant in Brampton to fulfil their contract with Metrolinx to build Alstom Citadis Spirit LRV cars for the TTC Finch West (ordered in 2017 with delivery beginning 2021 to be completed by 2023), Hurontario and Eglinton LRT lines.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] The Hurontario LRT maintenance facility is currently being built in Brampton.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] It is also the location of the Canadian Forces Army Reserve unit The Lorne Scots (Peel, Dufferin and Halton Regiment).
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] An automobile manufacturing facility was opened by American Motors (AMC) in 1960 as the Brampton Assembly Plant.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] In 1986, AMC developed a new, state-of-the-art operation at Bramalea.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] After AMC was acquired by Chrysler in 1987, AMC's Canadian division and its plants were absorbed; the older facility in Brampton closed in 1992.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] The newest factory was renamed Brampton Assembly; it is one of the city's largest employers, with almost 4,000 workers when running at capacity.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] The Algoma University at Brampton School of Business & Economics offers courses at Market Square Business Centre, 24 Queen Street East.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] The closest universities to Brampton (offering a wider range of programs) include York University in north Toronto and University of Toronto Mississauga.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] Along with that, Sheridan College's Davis Campus is another major public higher education institution serving Brampton which also has campuses in Oakville and Mississauga.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] In 2017, Davis added the Skilled Trades Centre, for training in skilled trades and apprenticeship programs, previously offered in Oakville.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] A plan by Toronto Metropolitan University, in partnership with Sheridan College was to establish a new campus in Brampton with a goal of opening in 2022 with $90 million in funding offered by the provincial government in April 2018.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] On 23 October 2018 however, the new Provincial government (elected in June) withdrew the funding for plans such as this, effectively cancelling the project.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] In 2022, the university, now renamed as Toronto Metropolitan, announced plans to open a medical school in Brampton.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] Brampton City Council gifted the university the Bramalea Civic Centre and most of the land it resides for this purpose.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] Two main school boards operate in Brampton: the Peel District School Board, which operates secular anglophone public schools, and Dufferin-Peel Catholic District School Board, which operates Catholic anglophone public schools.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] Under the Peel District School Board, the secondary schools are Bramalea, Brampton Centennial, Central Peel, Chinguacousy, Fletcher's Meadow, Harold M.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] Brathwaite, Heart Lake, Louise Arbour, Mayfield, North Park, Judith Nyman, Sandalwood Heights, Turner Fenton, David Suzuki, Castlebrooke Secondary School, and Jean Augustine, one of the newest.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] A total of 85 elementary and middle schools feed these high schools in the city.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] Under the Dufferin-Peel Catholic District School Board, the secondary schools are Cardinal Leger, Holy Name of Mary, Notre Dame, St.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] A total of 44 Catholic elementary and middle schools feed these high schools in the city.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] The *Conseil scolaire Viamonde* operates secular Francophone schools serving the area.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] The *Conseil scolaire catholique MonAvenir* operates Catholic Francophone schools serving the area.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] Several cultural entities in the city operate under the umbrella of the Brampton Arts Council.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] Located in the city is the Peel Art Gallery, Museum and Archives (PAMA, formerly the Peel Heritage Complex), which is run by the Region of Peel.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] The Rose Theatre (originally the Brampton Performing Arts Centre), opened in September 2006.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] The city had expected the facility to generate $2.7 million in economic activity the first year, growing to $19.8 million by the fifth year.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] The Rose Theatre far surpassed projections, attracting more than 137,000 patrons in its inaugural year, which exceeded its five-year goal.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] The arrival of so many new patrons downtown has stimulated the development of numerous new businesses nearby.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] A new Fountain Stage was unveiled in June 2008 at the nearby Garden Square.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] Brampton has eight library branches to serve its population.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] Festivals in the city include the annual Festival of Literary Diversity, a literary festival devoted to writers from underrepresented groups such as people of colour and LGBTQ writers.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] The Peel Art Gallery, Museum and Archives (PAMA) in Brampton includes a museum, art gallery, and archives.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] Since opening in 1968, the art gallery section (previously known as the Art Gallery of Peel) has exhibited local, national, and international artists, both contemporary and historical from their permanent collection.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] The City of Brampton's long-standing heritage conservation program was recognised with the 2011 Lieutenant Governor's Ontario Heritage Award for Community Leadership.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] In 2010, the city received an 'honourable mention' under the same provincial awards program.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] Major shopping areas include Bramalea City Centre, Shoppers World, and "big box centre" Trinity Commons.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] The downtown area has some retail; the Centennial Mall and the Brampton Mall are also of note.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] Brampton was one of the first areas where Rogers Cable offered its service.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] The city started a community access channel in the 1970s, which still operates.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] While some programs on the channel are produced in its Brampton studios, most are based in its Mississauga location.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] Christian specialty channel Vertical TV is based in Brampton.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] Brampton is the official city of license for two radio stations, CHLO and CFNY.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] Both stations address their programming toward the entire Greater Toronto Area rather than exclusively to Brampton.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] CFNY was located upstairs at 83 Kennedy Road until moving to Toronto in 1996.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] Brampton has been home to minor professional sports franchises at the CAA Centre, formerly the Powerade Centre.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] From 2013 to 2015, the Brampton A's played in the National Basketball League of Canada, but relocated to Orangeville, Ontario, to decrease costs of operations of switching the arena floor from ice hockey to basketball.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] From 2013 to 2020, the Brampton Beast played in the Central Hockey League and ECHL, but ceased operations during the COVID-19 pandemic in February 2021 after having not been able to play since March 2020.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] The numerous sporting venues and activities includes the outdoor ice path for skating through Gage Park.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] Chinguacousy Park includes a ski lift, a curling club, and Tennis Centre for multi-season activities.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] In the summer, amateur softball leagues abound.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] Crowds line the beaches at Professor's Lake for the annual outdoor "shagging" display.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] Since 1967, the Brampton Canadettes have hosted the annual Brampton Canadettes Easter Tournament in hockey.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] William Osler Health System operates two health facilities in the city.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] Grenville & William Davis Courthouse which houses branches for the Ontario Court of Justice and the Ontario Superior Court of Justice, is located at 7755 Hurontario Street (Hurontario Street at County Court).
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] The Brampton Jail is in the city it's now defunct and has turned into a museum.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] The Roy McMurtry Youth Centre is a juvenile detention centre located in Brampton.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] Local transit is provided by Brampton Transit, with connections to other systems such as MiWay, York Region Transit, GO Transit, and Toronto Transit Commission.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] Brampton Transit also operates a bus rapid transit system, "Züm" (pronounced Zoom), along Main/Hurontario Streets, Steeles Avenue, Queen Street/Highway 7, Bovaird Drive–Airport Road, and Queen Street West–Mississauga Road, which form the backbone to its bus network.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] There is GO Bus service to York University and subway stations at Yorkdale Mall and York Mills in Toronto.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] There are three GO Train stations in Brampton along the Kitchener line: Bramalea, Brampton and Mount Pleasant.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] Both Canadian National Railway (CN) and the Orangeville-Brampton Railway short line (formerly part of the Canadian Pacific Railway (CP) line) run through the city.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] CN's Intermodal Yards are located east of Airport Road between Steeles and Queen Street East.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] The CN Track from Toronto's Union Station is used by the Kitchener GO Transit Rail Corridor providing commuter rail to and from Toronto with rail station stops at Bramalea, Downtown Brampton, and Mount Pleasant.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] Via Rail connects through Brampton as part of the Quebec City-Windsor Corridor.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] Canada's busiest airport, Toronto Pearson International Airport (CYYZ), is located near Brampton, in Mississauga.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] For general aviation, the city is served by the privately owned Brampton Airport (CNC3), located to the north of the city in neighbouring Caledon.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] There is also a registered helipad Brampton National D (CPC4) located near the Brampton/Vaughan border, at Countryside Drive and Coleraine Drive.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] Brampton is served by several major transportation routes: Highway 401 from Toronto is a short distance south in Mississauga, and can be reached by Highway 410, which runs north–south through the middle of the city.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] Highway 407 runs along the southern portion of the city, just north of the boundary with Mississauga.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] Steeles Avenue, which runs north of the 407, is a thoroughfare continuing from Toronto.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] Queen Street is the city's main east–west street.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] Farther north, Bovaird Drive is another main artery.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] Sections of both Queen (eastern portion) and Bovaird (western portion) were part the former Highway 7, (now Regional Road 107), with Highway 410 being the route followed between the two streets.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] Main Street, part of the historic road, Hurontario Street (as well as Hurontario proper in the northern and southern parts of the city), and formerly Highway 10, is the city's main north–south artery.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p01] In the east end, Airport Road is a busy artery that is used as a route north to Wasaga Beach, a popular beach resort town.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p02] Four people from Brampton have received the Order of Canada: Robert William Bradford, former Director of the National Aviation Museum; Michael F.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p02] Clarke, director at Evergreen, the Yonge Street Mission for street youth in Toronto; Howard Pawley, professor and former Premier of Manitoba; and William G.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p02] Three Canadian premiers got their start in Brampton; Premiers Tobias Norris and Howard Pawley OC of Manitoba, and "Brampton Billy", Ontario premier William Grenville Davis CC.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p02] Other notable politicians include John Coyne, and Conservative opposition leader Gordon Graydon.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p02] Alberta politician and businessman Sir James A.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p02] Lougheed was born in Brampton, and served 30 years in Senate; Regina mayor David Lynch Scott was born here.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p02] President of the Treasury Board Tony Clement spent time as a Brampton MPP.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p02] John McDermid held various cabinet positions under Brian Mulroney, Bal Gosal Minister of State-Sport, and former Mayor Linda Jeffrey held cabinet positions at the provincial level.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p02] Incumbent mayor Patrick Brown served as leader of the Progressive Conservative Party of Ontario and as leader of the official opposition from 2015 until 2018 prior to serving as mayor.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p02] He was also a federal MP and provincial MPP, but not for Brampton.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p02] Ruby Dhalla represented the riding of Brampton—Springdale in the Canadian House of Commons from 2004 to 2011 as a member of the Liberal Party.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p02] Dhalla and British Columbia Conservative MP Nina Grewal were the first Sikh women to serve in the Canadian House of Commons.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p02] Parm Gill was elected as the member of parliament from the Conservative Party of Canada for the riding of Brampton-Springdale in 2011, who was also appointed as the Parliamentary Secretary to the Minister of Veteran Affairs in 2013.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p02] Jagmeet Singh began his political career in Brampton running in two elections in 2011, defeated in the federal election in May but elected Member of Provincial Parliament for Bramalea—Gore—Malton in October.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p02] In 2015 he became deputy leader of the Ontario New Democratic Party.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p02] In 2017 he became leader of the federal NDP, the first member of a visible minority to become permanent leader of a major federal party in Canada.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p02] Authors born in or living in Brampton include Rohinton Mistry, Jesse Thistle, Edo Van Belkom and Rupi Kaur (poet).
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p02] Visual arts notables from Brampton include etcher Caroline Helena Armington, Ronald Bloore, Member of the Order of Canada; Organiser and member of the "Regina Five" (1960), watercolourist Jack Reid, and William Ronald, who was raised in town.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p02] Animators David Feiss and Jay Stephens grew up here.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p02] Music acts from Brampton include Punk band The Flatliners, Indie Rock band Moneen, R&B singer Keshia Chanté, country singer Johnny Reid, "Metal Queen" Lee Aaron and pop singer Alyssa Reid.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p02] Country singer and "World Champion Yodeller" Donn Reynolds lived here from 1969 to 1997.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p02] Barry Stock, guitarist from Three Days Grace was raised in Brampton, and currently resides in Caledon.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p02] Singer Alessia Cara, hip-hop artist Roy Woods, and hip-hop artist Tory Lanez were also born in Brampton.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p02] Hip-hop record producer WondaGurl was also born in Brampton.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p02] Two notable comedians hail from Brampton: Scott Thompson and Russell Peters.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p02] Comedic actor Michael Cera was born and raised in Brampton.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p02] The twin actors Shawn Ashmore and Aaron Ashmore (*Smallville*) are Brampton-raised.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p02] The sibling actors Tyler Labine (*Mad Love*) and Kyle Labine were born in Brampton.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p02] Other Brampton-born or affiliated actors include Paulo Costanzo, Jordan Gavaris, Gemini Award winner Kris Lemche, Lara Jean Chorostecki, Sabrina Grdevich, Nicole Lyn, actor and producer David J.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p02] Phillips, reality TV star and art dealer Billy Jamieson, performer George R.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p02] Robertson, and performer Sidhu Moose Wala.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p02] Others include voice actor Brenna O'Brien, and on-air media personalities Cassie Campbell, Chris Connor, Chris Cuthbert and Scott McGillivray.
[src:dodge-magnum/brampton-p02] Brampton has two sister cities as well as active economic, historic, and cultural relationships with others.
[src:dodge-magnum/dodge-magnum] The **Dodge Magnum** is a nameplate used by several Dodge vehicles, at different times and on various markets.
[src:dodge-magnum/dodge-magnum] The name was first applied to a large Chrysler B platform-based 2-door coupe marketed from 1978 to 1979 sold in the United States and Canada.
[src:dodge-magnum/dodge-magnum] From the 2005 to the 2008 model years, the nameplate was revived for a Charger-based station wagon on the rear-wheel drive Chrysler LX platform, produced in Canada and sold on the American and Canadian market.
[src:dodge-magnum/dodge-magnum] In Brazil, the Magnum was a top-of-the-line version of the local Dodge Dart, produced from 1979 to 1981.
[src:dodge-magnum/dodge-magnum] In Mexico, the Dodge Magnum was a sporty rear-wheel drive two-door car based on Chrysler's M-body (American Dodge Diplomat/Plymouth Gran Fury).
[src:dodge-magnum/dodge-magnum] From 1983 to 1988 Dodge marketed a sporty two-door K-car as the "Magnum", with an available turbocharger engine from 1984 on.
[src:dodge-magnum/dodge-magnum] The Magnum was introduced for 1978 to supplement the Dodge Charger.
[src:dodge-magnum/dodge-magnum] It was sold in two forms, the "XE" and the "GT" and was the last vehicle to use the long running Chrysler B platform.
[src:dodge-magnum/dodge-magnum] The appearance was somewhat of a rounded off Charger, and was in response to getting a car that would be eligible for NASCAR that would be more aerodynamic, something that the 1975–1978 Charger was not.
[src:dodge-magnum/dodge-magnum] Styling features included four rectangular headlights behind retractable clear covers, with narrow opera windows, and an optional T-bar or power sunroof.
[src:dodge-magnum/dodge-magnum] The Magnum was well-featured with power steering, brakes and seats; the suspension included Chrysler's standard adjustable, longitudinal torsion bars, lower trailing links, and front and rear anti-sway bars.
[src:dodge-magnum/dodge-magnum] The base engine was the 318 cu in (5.2 L) V8 with Lean-Burn, while two and four-barrel carbureted 360 cu in (5.9 L) and 400 cu in (6.6 L) V8s were optional; weight was nearly 3,900 lb (1,800 kg).
[src:dodge-magnum/dodge-magnum] During the start of the 1979 model year, the 400 V8 engine was dropped from the options list as Chrysler stopped producing big-block V8 engines in production cars during the end of 1978 model year.
[src:dodge-magnum/dodge-magnum] Technology was advanced for the time with an onboard spark control computer from inception, electronic ignition, and a lockup torque converter.
[src:dodge-magnum/dodge-magnum] Only 3,704 1979 Dodge Magnum coupes included a T-Top.
[src:dodge-magnum/dodge-magnum] The mid-size B-body 1978–1979 Dodge Magnum coupe in the United States and Canada was an addition to Chrysler's line up that allowed Richard Petty to continue racing with a Mopar.
[src:dodge-magnum/dodge-magnum] For the 1978 NASCAR season, the 1974 Charger that Chrysler teams had continued to use was no longer eligible for competition.
[src:dodge-magnum/dodge-magnum] Chrysler worked on several car designs to smooth out the current 1975 bodied Charger into something that would be reasonably aerodynamic for the big racetracks and the Magnum design was settled on in the summer of 1977 for use in the 1978 racing season.
[src:dodge-magnum/dodge-magnum] While not as aerodynamic as the 1974 Charger body, the shape of the Magnum showed promise, and the Petty Enterprises built test cars reached 190 mph (310 km/h) on test runs.
[src:dodge-magnum/dodge-magnum] At first it seemed that out on the tracks the cars ran well with Petty almost winning his Daytona 125 (finishing second), and leading over 30 laps of the Daytona 500 until a blown front tire caused him to wreck.
[src:dodge-magnum/dodge-magnum] However, the lack of factory development support of the small-block Chrysler 360 V8 as a race engine was becoming more of a problem, and in high speed racing traffic the Magnum did not handle well.
[src:dodge-magnum/dodge-magnum] From August 1978, two to five independent teams showed up with Magnums in NASCAR races, until January 1981, when NASCAR switched to smaller bodied cars.
[src:dodge-magnum/dodge-magnum] The Magnum never enjoyed the racing heritage of its predecessors, but it was not without its own achievements.
[src:dodge-magnum/dodge-magnum] Petty scored 7 top five finishes in his 17 races with the car, and Bonnett won three poles and scored 5 top five finishes with his.
[src:dodge-magnum/dodge-magnum] Petty recognized the Magnum with a commemorative decal, depicting his famous number 43 emblazoned on a Magnum for his 1992 Fan Appreciation Tour.
[src:dodge-magnum/dodge-magnum] Though Petty never won a race in a Magnum, his son, Kyle Petty drove one of his father's year-old Dodge Magnums in his first race (1979 Daytona ARCA 200), and won.
[src:dodge-magnum/dodge-magnum] Kyle raced in five NASCAR races using the left-over Magnums in 1979, but wrecked them beyond reasonable repair by the 1980 Daytona 125.
[src:dodge-magnum/dodge-magnum] As of December 2012, only two NASCAR Magnums still existed; one (an ex-Petty car) resides in the Talladega NASCAR museum, and the other; (Marty Robbins' 1978 Magnum No.
[src:dodge-magnum/dodge-magnum] 42) has been restored and is owned by a private party in southern California.
[src:dodge-magnum/dodge-magnum] From 1969 until 1981 the Dodge Dart was produced in the old Simca Factory in São Bernardo do Campo, São Paulo, Brazil.
[src:dodge-magnum/dodge-magnum] More than 92,000 cars were sold in this period.
[src:dodge-magnum/dodge-magnum] They were built with minor changes from the original model, starting in 1969, and were all largely based on the 1968 Dart GT (and GTS).
[src:dodge-magnum/dodge-magnum] For its last three years of production, a two-door upper trim level version of the Dart was sold as the *Magnum*, featuring the 318 cu in V8 engine used in all Dodge coupé and sedan models in Brazil.
[src:dodge-magnum/dodge-magnum] A unique fiberglass front fascia that included four headlights to give it a more modern look was used, while the rear end was very similar to the 1975 American Dart (the Dart model from the same year having been identical to the Swinger from USA).
[src:dodge-magnum/dodge-magnum] The Magnum (top of the line) was sold as a separate model from the Dart (bottom line), despite being technically almost identical to the Dart.
[src:dodge-magnum/dodge-magnum] In 1980, the F-body cars were discontinued in Mexico, as well in the U.S., so the compact cars Dodge Dart (using the front of the Volaré and the rear of the Aspen), Valiant Volaré (using the front of the Aspen and the rear of the Volaré), and sporty Valiant Super Bee, were dropped for this year.
[src:dodge-magnum/dodge-magnum] In 1979, Chrysler de México introduced the Chrysler LeBaron based on the M-body platform, and two years later it introduced the Dodge Diplomat as the Dodge Dart.
[src:dodge-magnum/dodge-magnum] These were very similar to the American Plymouth Gran Fury in appearance and trim, but had Chrysler's Rallye wheels instead of deluxe wheel covers.
[src:dodge-magnum/dodge-magnum] All of the window trim was flat black; with only the bumpers and the grille chromed.
[src:dodge-magnum/dodge-magnum] Both the front fascia and the front fenders wore "Magnum" lettering, with a 5.9 L decal on the fenders as well.
[src:dodge-magnum/dodge-magnum] The Mexican Dodge Magnum was offered only for the 1981–1982 model years.
[src:dodge-magnum/dodge-magnum] Four engines were offered for the Mexican Dodge Magnum K: a 2.2 L SOHC I-4 (K-Trans-4, 1983–86), a turbocharged 2.2 L SOHC I-4 (1984–86) and two 2.5 L SOHC I-4s, with and without turbocharger (1987–88).
[src:dodge-magnum/dodge-magnum] When it was introduced, the Mexican Dodge Magnum 400 Turbo was advertised as "Mexico's fastest car" in the TV commercials of the time, and it surely was in 1985, when the "Fox" (1979–84) 5.0 L Mexican Ford Mustang was dropped from the catalog of Ford Mexico.
[src:dodge-magnum/dodge-magnum] In 1984, the Mexican Magnum 400 Turbo was the closest thing to an American Dodge Daytona Turbo south of the border.
[src:dodge-magnum/dodge-magnum] For the 1987 season, the turbocharger received an intercooler and the power from the turbo engine changed from 140 to 150 hp (112 kW).
[src:dodge-magnum/dodge-magnum] The K-car based Magnum was replaced by the Mexican Chrysler Shadow GTS for the 1989 model year.
[src:dodge-magnum/dodge-magnum] The Magnum name was revived in 2004 for the 2005 model year, as a station wagon based on the Chrysler LX platform.
[src:dodge-magnum/dodge-magnum] The Magnum had four engine options; the *SE* features the 190 hp (142 kW) 2.72 L LH V6, the *SXT* had the 250 hp (190 kW) 3.5 L V6, and the *RT* had the new 340 hp (254 kW) 5.7 L Hemi V8.
[src:dodge-magnum/dodge-magnum] The SRT8 has a 425 hp (317 kW) 6.1 L Hemi engine.
[src:dodge-magnum/dodge-magnum] All-wheel drive became an option in 2005 on SXT and RT models.
[src:dodge-magnum/dodge-magnum] The SRT8, AWD SXT, and the RT use a Mercedes-Benz-derived 5-speed automatic transmission, while all other models use a four-speed automatic.
[src:dodge-magnum/dodge-magnum] The Magnum was built at the Brampton Assembly Plant, near Toronto, Ontario, Canada, from 2004 to the end of model year 2008.
[src:dodge-magnum/dodge-magnum] The Dodge Magnum is based on the rear-wheel-drive Chrysler LX platform with Chrysler executives confirming that structural elements of the car's foundation such as the toe board, safety cage architecture, as well as the load-path philosophy being utilized by then-partner, Mercedes-Benz.
[src:dodge-magnum/dodge-magnum] Mercedes executives also confirmed that several individual components of the car are derived from the Mercedes-Benz E-Class (W211) and S-Class of the era.
[src:dodge-magnum/dodge-magnum] Later models also feature a Mercedes-Benz-derived laser key ignition system in place of the traditional metal key.
[src:dodge-magnum/dodge-magnum] AWD models also benefited from the use of Mercedes-Benz's 4MATIC system, including transfer case components.
[src:dodge-magnum/dodge-magnum] The Magnum was on *Car and Driver's* Ten Best list for 2005.
[src:dodge-magnum/dodge-magnum] A higher performance SRT8 version debuted at the 2005 Los Angeles Auto Show.
[src:dodge-magnum/dodge-magnum] The SRT8 was based on a concept car that was displayed at the 2003 Los Angeles Auto Show.
[src:dodge-magnum/dodge-magnum] It went on sale in 2005 as a 2006 model.
[src:dodge-magnum/dodge-magnum] Like the 300C SRT8, it featured the new 6.1 L (370 cu in) Hemi engine, which produced 425 hp (317 kW).
[src:dodge-magnum/dodge-magnum] 20-inch wheels, firmer suspension, bigger Brembo brakes, new lower-body treatment, and a revised front and rear-fascia completed the transformation.
[src:dodge-magnum/dodge-magnum] The SRT8 was named "Best New Modern Muscle Car" in the 2006 Canadian Car of the Year contest.
[src:dodge-magnum/dodge-magnum] 2007 and 2008 also saw the addition of the R/T "Red Badge" *29R* Road and Track package, which featured all of the SRT8 options except the 6.1 Hemi engine and Brembo brakes.
[src:dodge-magnum/dodge-magnum] In Europe and Australia, the Magnum was sold as the Chrysler 300 Touring.
[src:dodge-magnum/dodge-magnum] It was essentially the same as the U.S.-market Magnum, but with the Chrysler 300C's front end and interior, and right-hand-drive for Australia and the U.K.
[src:dodge-magnum/dodge-magnum] The 300C Touring added an available 3.0 L CRD Turbo Diesel version.
[src:dodge-magnum/dodge-magnum] The 300C Touring was assembled in Austria.
[src:dodge-magnum/dodge-magnum] For the 2008 model year, the Magnum received a facelift as well as an updated interior in line with that of the Dodge Charger.
[src:dodge-magnum/dodge-magnum] The front fascia sported new aggressively squared off headlights and a smaller rectangular grille more reminiscent of the Charger.
[src:dodge-magnum/dodge-magnum] The Magnum SE, SXT, And RT models received two all new colors for the 2008 model year; Mineral Gray, and Light Sandstone.
[src:dodge-magnum/dodge-magnum] The SRT8 variant gained a new hood scoop, more aggressive front fascia, a smaller, honeycomb mesh grille, and larger lower grille with brake cooling ducts.
[src:dodge-magnum/dodge-magnum] New colors such as TorRed and Steel Blue Metallic, originally introduced in 2007, were carried over to the face lifted 2008 SRT8 Magnums as well as other trim levels.
[src:dodge-magnum/dodge-magnum] These new changes brought the car closer to its Charger platform mate, away from the Chrysler 300.
[src:dodge-magnum/dodge-magnum] However, with its cancellation that same model year, the 2008 facelift was only available for one year.
[src:dodge-magnum/dodge-magnum] On November 1, 2007, Chrysler announced that, as part of its restructuring plans, the Dodge Magnum would be one of four models discontinued after the 2008 model year.
[src:dodge-magnum/dodge-magnum] In Chrysler's words: "The Magnum, along with the PT Cruiser convertible, the Crossfire, and the Pacifica were not earning their keep".
[src:dodge-magnum/dodge-magnum] The Dodge Magnum (along with the short-wheelbase Dodge Caravan) has been replaced by the Dodge Journey.
[src:dodge-magnum/dodge-magnum] A popular modification has been to change the front fascia of the Magnum to that of the 2005-2010 Chrysler 300; the commonality of parts and design of the LX cars means such a swap requires little to no custom fabrication.
[src:dodge-magnum/dodge-magnum] It's also possible to swap on the Charger's front fascia, but doing so is generally a more involved process.
[src:dodge-magnum/dodge-magnum] While the Magnum front fascia can be swapped with that of the Dodge Challenger, it is not a direct bolt-on swap, despite the cars sharing the same platform.
